Background

Randomized Controlled Trial in Samburu County, Kenya

  • BOMA Rural Entrepreneur Access Program
    • Poverty Graduation for Women
    • Targets poorest in communities
    • Cash grant ($200 + $100)
    • Savings group (3-5 women)
    • Health insurance for two years
    • Mentor + business training
  • Index-Based Livestock Insurance (IBLI)
    • Uses satellites to monitor drought conditions
    • Sends (mobile) money when droughts strike.

Samburu County

  • Majority nomadic pastoralists.
  • Women stay at base camp with children and few livestock.
  • Men travel to satellite camps with herd in search of pasture.

Separate Spheres and Livestock Insurance

How involved are you in decisions regardingâ€¦ ?

so how does livestock insurance benefit women?

Her Problem

Wife allocates her income plus a transfer \(t\) from the husband between consumption \(c_w\), household public goods \(z\), and investment \(k_w\).

\[ v_w(y_w,y_m)=\max_{c_w, z, k_w} u_w(c_w, z) + \beta_wE[v(y_w',y_m')], \] production \(f(k_w)\) experiences shock \(\epsilon\) \[ y_w' = f(k_w)\epsilon_w \] and \[ c_w+z+k_w\leq y_w + t(y_m, y_w) \]

His Problem

Husband allocates his budget between a transfer to the wife, his own consumption, and investment.

\[ v_m(y_m, y_w)=\max_{c_m, t, k_m} u_m(c_m, z(t, y_w)) + \beta_wE[v(y_m', y_w')] \] where \[ y_m' = f(k_m)\epsilon_m \] and \[ c_m+t+k_m\leq y_m \]

Model Result: Womensâ€™ investments at greater risk than mensâ€™ during droughts

When droughts strike:

  • If women have little capital/income, men maintain transfers ensure public goods production (school fees, medical bills, food).
  • If women have their own income, men reduce transfers.
  • Women know this, which reduces their returns to investment (esp.Â if man is not poor) - may be better to spend a grant today on consumption, food, and education.

Whose sphere does insurance belong to?

Insurance is a new asset type - whose income does it enter?

Index Based Livestock Insurance seems to fit in the male sphere.

What about family drought insurance?

Experiment: Overview

387 couples, picked randomly from respondents in a subset of regions from our baseline survey.

Conducted by 4 teams who worked with groups of ~8 couples at a time across Samburu County.

Compensation: 300 KSh for attending plus incentive based on performance.

Experiment: Framing

Livestock:

  • Droughts threaten livestock.
  • Insurance can help protect livestock.

Family:

  • Droughts threaten livestock and also make it hard to pay for household needs.
  • Insurance can help protect livestock and can also be used to pay household expenses, school fees, and more.

Experiment: Randomization

At the session level, we randomize framing and starting budgets.

Experiment: Couples Sessions

Women insure more under family framing, men insure less

Implications

  • Naming and framing of financial products matters, especially when novel.
  • Carefully designed asset protection for durable empowerment.

Bringing Family Insurance to the Real World

  • In reality, we can have both household and family insurance.
  • Concept: allocate livestock units according to TLUs, family insurance based on assessment of household costs during drought (school fees, food, etc)
  • Use promotional videos to standardize (part of) marketing, run experiment within existing RCT.
